{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:50:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15189"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15189"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.09,0.64,0.05,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7880"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100224"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7880"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15189"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82622"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"2119"},{"type":"tags","id":"2855"},{"type":"tags","id":"3508"},{"type":"tags","id":"3512"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34438"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100224"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of right foot swelling. He has a 15-year history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. He also has a history of Graves\u0027 disease. His medications include metformin, gliclazide, insulin glargine, carbimazole, perindopril, and atorvastatin. He reports intermittent insulin adherence. He returned from an overseas holiday four months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His right foot and ankle are markedly swollen, warm, and erythematous. Despite the significant swelling, he reports minimal pain. There is no break in the skin. The foot has reduced sensation to light touch and vibration. Collapse of the arch of the midfoot is noted. Rheumatoid factor is mildly elevated. Cyclic citrullinated peptide (CCP) antibody is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid arthritis","Deep vein thrombosis","Diabetes mellitus","Gout","Cellulitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of Charcot arthropathy (diabetic neuroathropathy), a condition most commonly caused by poorly controlled \u003Cstrong\u003Ediabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E. Charcot arthropathy has a multifactorial pathogenesis, due to both vascular and mechanical factors contributed to by suboptimally-controlled diabetes, peripheral and autonomic neuropathy, and changes to the bone architecture. The key features are a red, hot, swollen foot with peripheral neuropathy. Most patients experience some pain, but typically minimal or of lesser severity than that which might be expected from the findings. The patient\u0027s poor insulin adherence has likely contributed to the development of diabetic neuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with symmetrical joint involvement, morning stiffness, and pain. While this patient has a mildly elevated rheumatoid factor, the negative CCP antibody and unilateral presentation make this diagnosis less likely. Furthermore, rheumatoid arthritis is typically a more painful presentation. \u003Cstrong\u003EDeep vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause unilateral leg swelling and warmth. However, it is typically painful and does not cause the degree of joint destruction seen in Charcot arthropathy. The prolonged timing since air travel (four months) makes this less likely. \u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute episodes of severe joint pain and inflammation, often affecting isolated joints such as the first metatarsophalangeal joint. \u003Cstrong\u003ECellulitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with acute onset of erythema, warmth, and tenderness. While the foot is warm and red, the chronic nature of symptoms, lack of pain, and intact skin make infection less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECharcot arthropathy occurs due to a combination of peripheral neuropathy and repeated microtrauma leading to progressive joint destruction. The loss of protective pain sensation often leads to continued weight-bearing despite joint damage. Early recognition is crucial as the condition can lead to severe deformity and disability if untreated. Management includes offloading the affected foot and optimising glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Poorly controlled diabetes is the most common cause of Charcot arthropathy due to its effects on peripheral nerves and blood vessels.","The combination of peripheral neuropathy and repeated microtrauma leads to progressive joint destruction in Charcot arthropathy."],"references":["Harris A, Violand M. Charcot Neuropathic Osteoarthropathy (Charcot Joint) In: StatPearls [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470164/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82622"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15189"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82622"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-24T22:12:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-24T22:12:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7880"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100224"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"e